        i0.ɵɵelementStart(140, "p", 17);
        i0.ɵɵtext(141, " He gasped out, \u201CI was innocent. Artemis, you? My goddess, your huntsman is dying.\u201D");
        i0.ɵɵelement(142, "br");
        i0.ɵɵtext(143, " \u201CAnd no other can take your place, dearest of men to me,\u201D she told him. Hippolytus turned his eyes from her radiance to Theseus brokenhearted.");
        i0.ɵɵelement(144, "br");
        i0.ɵɵtext(145, " \u201CFather, dear Father,\u201D he said. \u201CIt was not your fault.\u201D");
        i0.ɵɵelement(146, "br");
        i0.ɵɵtext(147, " \u201CIf only I could die for you,\u201D Theseus cried.");
        i0.ɵɵelement(148, "br");
        i0.ɵɵtext(149, " The calm sweet voice of the goddess broke in on their anguish. \u201CTake your son in your arms, Theseus,\u201D she said. \u201CIt was not you that killed him. It was Aphrodite. Know this, that he will never be forgotten. In song and story men will remember him.\u201D");
        i0.ɵɵelement(150, "br");
        i0.ɵɵelementEnd();
        i0.ɵɵelementStart(151, "p", 17);
        i0.ɵɵtext(152, " She vanished from sight, but Hippolytus, too, was gone. He had started on the road that leads down to the realm of death. ");
        i0.ɵɵelementEnd();
        i0.ɵɵelementStart(153, "p", 17);
        i0.ɵɵtext(154, " Theseus\u2019 death, also, was wretched. He was at the court of a friend, King Lycomedes, where a few years later Achilles was to hide disguised as a girl. Some say that Theseus had gone there because Athens had banished him. At all events, the King, his friend and his host, killed him, we are not told why. ");
